Finally, we discuss a straightforward modification to the above protocol to make better connection with the experiment. Instead of considering a single NP located at the middle of the NT, we now generalize to a dense covering of NPs. Specifically, we take one NP per unit cell of the NT (clearly an approximation, but one which recovers the essential physics of the problem). The effect of the hybridization between NT and NP at each unit cell can be simply incorporated on the level of the NT Green’s functions by modifying En. The dense NP coverage has a cooperative effect on the NT density of states, and therefore the conductance through each NP. Denoting the conductance between the NT and a target molecule attached to a NP at site n as Gn, we now compute the total conductance as Gtotal =  ∑nGn.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathop {\sum}\nolimits_n {G_n.}$$\end{document} This is plotted in Fig. 5f, and captures the basic features of the experiment, including the field-activated enhancement and threshold behavior.
